<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900802-0150</DOCNO><DOCID>900802-0150.</DOCID><HL>   International:   EC Commission Negotiates   On Cut in Airbus Subsidies   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   EUROP F.ABI</CO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   BRUSSELS -- European Community Commission sources said theEC may substantially cut production subsidies to the Europeanconsortium Airbus Industrie to try to resolve a long disputewith the U.S.   The sources said commission negotiators, acting on behalfof the four countries involved in the consortium -- Britain,France, Spain and West Germany -- have offered to cut allproduction subsidies on aircraft with more than 100 seats.This category would include the Airbus 330 and 340 aircraftthat are at the heart of the dispute.</LP><TEXT>   Figures weren't immediately available on the amount of thesubsidies covered by the EC offer.   The U.S. trade delegation in Washington has indicated thatif the commission made such a move, it wouldn't take theissue to the Geneva-based General Agreement on Tariffs andTrade.   The U.S.'s original deadline for resolving the dispute wasTuesday, but now negotiations between the two sides are setto continue.   Sources say the commission is also offering to cutsubsidies for development costs by as much as 50%. The U.S.wants no more than 35% of the costs subsidized.</TEXT></DOC>